Caveat Emptor.

All of your DNA comes from your ancestors. But all of your ancestors are not represented in your DNA. You get half of your genes from your mom, and half from your dad. But because of recombination, you don't necessarily get a quarter of your genes from your grandparents. In fact, there is a chance, at least in theory, that you don't have DNA from one of your grandparents.

It goes without saying that you don't get DNA from every one single of your sixteen great-great-grandparents. If one of those grandparents was Navajo, but you didn't get any DNA from him/her, then you would be of Navajo descent but it wouldn't show up in your DNA.

Ancestry trees aren't DNA ancestry trees or vice versa. So your DNA may says "100 percent Asian" but that doesn't mean you do n't have European ancestry. It just means you didn't get any "European" DNA.
